A quick fully lined @wickettandcraig glazed harness belt. 

This belt was needed in a hurry so my leather choice was limited. On hand was some incredible brown glazed harness, but at only 3-4oz it was to thin for a belt. I doubled it up and stitched the perimeter. 

I don’t expect this belt to get heavy use so we will see how well this holds up over time.

Also, belts are coming back! Antique Brass and Nickel buckles like what’s shown here with Black and Cognac 8-10oz Vincenzo Leather from @balticleathersupply

I did something I haven’t done before…

I had some orange Sully lying around and decided to try and line an Orko wallet. We will see how it holds up over time, maybe I’ll add it as an option for those of you looking for something a little different.

#vegtan #luxuryleather #menswallet

24-hrs in, this is a chunky wallet. 🤣

I forgot to skive the interior lining which added 2mm of thickness and I got carried away and lined the pockets which added another 2mm…this thing clocks in at about 8-9mm. 

I don’t ever line pockets because of the use that top edge will get, we’ll see how it holds up over time but I’m sure the glued edge will come apart.

#leatherwork #alwayslearning #takerisks

Step by Step Instructions Below 👇🏻 

Step 1: Cut the sandpaper to the width of the mandrel.

Step 2: Cut a slot in the end of the sandpaper to insert into the slot in the mandrel.

Step 3: Secure the sandpaper to the mandrel with a piece of tape.

Step 4: Roll the sandpaper onto the mandrel. Make sure you keep it as tight as possible.

Step 5: Secure the sandpaper with a small elastic.

These custom sandpaper bits make the edge finishing processes significantly faster. And when you combine them with sanding blocks of the same grit you ensure a perfectly flat edge.  These sanding blocks are form @junlinleather
